<script>
    import Preview from "$lib/components/Preview.svelte"
</script>

"I'll make the text slightly gray... it looks more modern." Then nobody can actually read it. Contrast isn't about aesthetics. It's about whether people can actually read your UI, or if they'll need a magnifying glass and a prayer..

## The Standards

WCAG (the accessibility police) says:

- **3:1** — minimum for large text (18px+ or 14px+ bold)
- **4.5:1** — minimum for normal body text
- **7:1** — preferred for easy reading

Check your ratios at contrast-ratio.com or in your browser's DevTools.

The "trendy light gray on white" look? Often fails even for large text.

## What Actually Works

On white background:

```
gray-300  → 1.6:1   fails
gray-400  → 2.5:1   fails
gray-500  → 3.9:1   passes large text only
gray-600  → 5.9:1   passes everything
gray-700  → 8.5:1   solid
gray-800  → 12.6:1  strong
gray-900  → 17.4:1  almost black
```

Body text: use gray-600 minimum. Prefer gray-700 or darker.

Placeholder text and secondary metadata: gray-500 is acceptable.

White text on colored buttons: check the background color. A light blue isn't enough. You need at least blue-600.

